    <h3>Here are a few tips for writing yellow sentences.</h3>
    <br><br>
    Bold Statements
    "It was over before it had begun."
    <br><br>
    Authors often use yellow sentences like this to start a story. Bold statements incite curiosity, compelling readers to read on. They also influence the sentences that follow them, casting their meaning like a shadow.
    <br><br>
    Short Descriptions of Action
    "He punched. He kicked. He stomped."
    <br><br>
    Unlike green and blue sentences, yellow sentences don't leave much of an impression. (They are just too simple.) But they make up for this in impact, shooting straight to the imagination like bullets. (Pow! Pow!) This makes them ideal for when an author needs to keep things moving quickly.
    <br><br>
    Combining Sentences
    "None of the witnesses, not the judge, nor the bailiff, nor the prosecutor, would speak of it. Doing so would mean the end of their careers."
    <br><br>
    Notice how the bold yellow sentence provides a sense of definition for the mysterious green sentence?
